.TH "ubi_io_write_vid_hdr" 9 "ubi_io_write_vid_hdr" "May 2021" "Kernel Hacker's Manual" LINUX
.SH NAME
ubi_io_write_vid_hdr \- write a volume identifier header.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "int" ubi_io_write_vid_hdr
.BI "(struct ubi_device *ubi "  ","
.BI "int pnum "  ","
.BI "struct ubi_vid_io_buf *vidb "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "ubi" 12
UBI device description object
.IP "pnum" 12
the physical eraseblock number to write to
.IP "vidb" 12
the volume identifier buffer to write
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
This function writes the volume identifier header described by \fIvid_hdr\fP to
physical eraseblock \fIpnum\fP. This function automatically fills the
\fIvidb->hdr->magic\fP and the \fIvidb->hdr->version\fP fields, as well as calculates
header CRC checksum and stores it at vidb->hdr->hdr_crc.

This function returns zero in case of success and a negative error code in
case of failure. If -EIO is returned, the physical eraseblock probably went
bad.
